# Comments and Docstrings

Code should read like a poem. Default to no comments and no docstrings — a well-named function with clear arguments and a readable body is self-documenting.

Comments and docstrings are allowed only when the logic is genuinely non-obvious: a complex algorithm, a subtle invariant, or a train of thought the code alone cannot carry. If you want to comment on straightforward code, rename or refactor until the comment isn't needed.

```python
# BAD — comment restates what the code already says
def lookup(dependency_name: str) -> dict | None:
    """Look up a dependency in the component database."""
    # Normalise the name before comparing
    needle = _normalise(dependency_name)
    for component in db["components"]:
        ...

# GOOD — the names carry the meaning
def lookup(dependency_name: str) -> dict | None:
    needle = _normalise(dependency_name)
    for component in db["components"]:
        ...

# GOOD — non-obvious behaviour worth explaining
def parse_version(hex_string: str) -> str:
    # OpenSSL encodes version as a packed hex constant: 0x1010107fL = 1.1.1g
    major = (value >> 28) & 0xF
    ...
```